2:30 I have to make a comment about this. The problem with plastic bags and straws and just plastic in general, is not the CO2 emissions, but the negative impact of plastic in the environment. Environment =/= climate.

I'm sure you're perfectly aware of this, but I feel like it's important to point out so people don't misunderstand your argument here.

True, although there is also a climate connection - as plastic is a petroleum product, one way the oil industry plans to remain viable for longer is through switching from producing so much petroleum-based fuel to producing more petroleum-based plastics. This will mean fossil fuels remain financially sustainable for longer, and may allow companies to squeeze a few more decades of profit out of oil exploration while suppressing advancements towards clean energy through market competition. It's a stop gap measure - the oil industry still won't last forever and government regulation may intervene (big maybe) - but we may not have a few extra decades to lose here.

Sir at what age can I become a researcher (like the actual scientists we all imagined who do research and publish theories) if I were to take a physics degree?
@Martin Nov√°ƒçek Thank you very much!

This very much depends on what you would classify as "a researcher". If you were to undertake the classic path of Bachalor's -> Master's -> Ph. D. and then got employed fresh out of your Ph. D. programme (although it's usually better to do some postdocs (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Postdoctoral_researcher) before doing that), you could be permanently employed at the age of 27-32 (with the average somewhere around 29). However, the whole point of Ph. D. is learning how to properly do research (reducing the number to about 25), and the final year of your Master's is also spent doing research, although it's usually under guidance from some advisor, so the final answer could be 24. That being said, most countries offer some option for high school students to have an internship at some research institute, so I would advise you to look for something like that, as you could get a sense of what does it take to be a researcher and test whether it's right for you :) If you have any more questions, definitely ask away :D
